<DOC><DOCNO> AP880229-0104 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-29-88 1234EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-OfficerSlain     02-29 0278</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Officer Slain,0285</SECOND><HEAD>Three Arrested In Officer's Slaying</HEAD><BYLINE>By WALT SMITH</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   One of three men arrested on capital murderwarrants in the shooting death of an off-duty police officer hadpreviously pleaded guilty to an assault on another police officerand was on parole, authorities said.   Another of the men arrested was on parole after a robberyconviction.   ``This is rather indicative of how the criminal justice systemis working,'' Capt. John Holt said Sunday.   The officer's death was the seventh in six shootings involvingpolice this year. In addition to three dead police officers, fourcivilians have been killed by police this year.   Vincent Edward Cooks, 23, was arrested Sunday in Houston, andTony Ray Harvey, 23, and Tracy Dewayne Stallworth, 27, werearrested Saturday, Holt said at a news conference Sunday.   Holt and Lt. Ron Waldrop told reporters that other details ofthe arrests were not available because the investigation into thedeath of officer Gary D. McCarthy was continuing.   Cooks began serving a five-year sentence in December 1986 andwas paroled on Aug. 4, 1987. He initially was charged withattempted capital murder of a police officer, but Houston policeSgt. V.W. West said Cooks pleaded no contest in September 1985 to areduced charge of aggravated assault.   Harvey was paroled Jan. 18 after serving 18 months of a six-yearsentence for aggravated robbery and unauthorized use of a motorvehicle, Holt said.   Harvey was being held in lieu of $500,000 bond while bond wasset at $300,000 for Stallworth. Cooks was to be returned to Dallasfrom Houston, said an officer who refused to give his name.</TEXT></DOC>